The `Stringer` interface is defined by `fmt`. Any type that implements `String() string` will be used by `fmt` functions for formatting.

```go
type Stringer interface {
    String() string
}

func (p Person) String() string {
    return fmt.Sprintf("%s (%d)", p.Name, p.Age)
}
```

Built-in function that returns the length of a value: number of elements in an array, slice, string, map, or channel buffer.

```go
n := len(mySlice)
if len(s) == 0 { /* empty */ }
for i := 0; i < len(arr); i++ { }
```

Built-in function that regains control of a panicking goroutine. Only useful inside deferred functions.

```go
defer func() {
    if r := recover(); r != nil {
        log.Println("Recovered:", r)
    }
}()
```

The `error` interface is the conventional interface for representing an error condition.

```go
type error interface {
    Error() string
}

if err != nil {
    return err
}
```

`comparable` is the constraint for types that support `==` and `!=`. Used as a type constraint in generics.

```go
func Contains[T comparable](s []T, v T) bool {
    for _, item := range s {
        if item == v { return true }
    }
    return false
}
```

